WEBVTT

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:08.120
Now, when I was growing up, there was definitely a stereotype on who and what a coder was.

00:00:08.120 --> 00:00:13.200
And I decided to start this talk by using AI to ask a bunch of different tools,

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:15.640
show me a coder.

00:00:15.640 --> 00:00:17.799
And they all showed me this guy.

00:00:17.799 --> 00:00:25.200
This guy right here, with this haircut, these glasses, that amount of coffee and pizza,

00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:26.440
he's a coder.

00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:31.200
So at least according to AI, there's definitely still a stereotype.

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:34.919
Hopefully that's not offensive to anybody who has this haircut.

00:00:34.919 --> 00:00:41.360
But obviously that's not really me.

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:48.119
I was a first-generation college grad by day, hair model by night, and I certainly did not

00:00:48.119 --> 00:00:52.320
identify or really have anything to do with coding.

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:57.439
And then I started towards my PhD, and sort of the amount, the size, and the complexity

00:00:57.439 --> 00:01:01.000
of biological data I was going to need to analyze exploded.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:05.320
And I realized, oh, crap, I'm going to have to learn some coding.

00:01:05.320 --> 00:01:08.980
And I'm going to have to do that on my own, because that was not originally my plan.

00:01:08.980 --> 00:01:13.400
And while I was in a super supportive environment, and there was a lot of great people that really

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:19.199
supported me, it felt really lonely and kind of isolating, because I was a biologist.

00:01:19.199 --> 00:01:21.400
What am I doing with computers?

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:25.040
But then I participated in a hackathon, and it hit me.

00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:31.040
What if coding wasn't an exclusive skill, but an accessible social adventure?

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:34.000
And I really got excited about that idea.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.760
And I've spent the better part of ten years working primarily in nontraditional training

00:01:39.760 --> 00:01:42.480
methods with a wide variety of communities.

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:48.040
So everything from indigenous networks to high school students to medical librarians

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:50.199
and bench biologists.

00:01:50.199 --> 00:01:54.360
And there's one thing that sort of kept coming out over and over again with a lot of the

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:56.160
people I work with.

00:01:56.160 --> 00:02:02.519
And they also didn't see themselves or even want to be coders.

00:02:02.519 --> 00:02:08.119
You know, they really just wanted to analyze their research data, understand their community

00:02:08.119 --> 00:02:11.559
health risks, or explore their hobbies.

00:02:11.559 --> 00:02:13.679
Pokemon data, fantasy football.

00:02:13.679 --> 00:02:19.279
And coding was sort of this necessary evil that they needed to do the thing that they

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:20.360
were excited about.

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:25.479
And inevitably, these folks would end up getting stuck on something, and they would go to the

00:02:25.479 --> 00:02:31.320
internet, where inevitably they would end up on Stack Overflow.

00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:37.119
And on Stack Overflow, somebody will tell you, go read the fricking manual.

00:02:37.119 --> 00:02:40.559
And obviously that's super disheartening.

00:02:40.559 --> 00:02:45.240
And if you're starting to learn and somebody tells you that, you may just stop right there.

00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:50.399
But what's even more fascinating to me is this idea that even troubleshooting should

00:02:50.399 --> 00:02:51.399
be solo.

00:02:51.399 --> 00:02:52.399
Right?

00:02:52.399 --> 00:02:53.399
You go off.

00:02:53.399 --> 00:02:54.399
You go learn it.

00:02:54.399 --> 00:02:55.399
You go read it.

00:02:55.399 --> 00:02:56.399
You go fix it.

00:02:56.399 --> 00:03:01.199
And to me, like, that really struck me as, like, an interesting thing.

00:03:01.199 --> 00:03:06.160
The other thing is, for a lot of folks, they don't want to have beautiful code.

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:08.600
They're not interested in the technical nitty gritty.

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:11.320
They just want to do the cool thing.

00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:14.800
And a lot of the ways we offer help isn't that.

00:03:14.800 --> 00:03:18.639
So, you know, some of us, we do love to code.

00:03:18.639 --> 00:03:23.660
But for most of the people that I work with, they code to do what they love.

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:29.559
So how can we create spaces, environments, and places where things are more social?

00:03:29.559 --> 00:03:33.639
That things are about the doing, the building of the thing versus the doing of the thing?

00:03:33.639 --> 00:03:38.600
And I've kind of come up with these three basic concepts that kind of happen over and

00:03:38.600 --> 00:03:41.860
over again in these kinds of spaces.

00:03:41.860 --> 00:03:43.160
And the first is trust.

00:03:43.160 --> 00:03:44.160
Right?

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:51.199
To create a safe, collaborative environment where people feel comfortable asking questions,

00:03:51.199 --> 00:03:56.240
expressing interest, and also just saying frustrations.

00:03:56.240 --> 00:03:58.160
You also want things to be accessible, right?

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:03.199
You want to lower those barriers of entry, make it not so scary, have people have a starting

00:04:03.199 --> 00:04:05.880
point so they don't feel like they're drowning.

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:09.399
And also, and more importantly, and actually this kind of came out in our previous speaker,

00:04:09.399 --> 00:04:10.399
right?

00:04:10.399 --> 00:04:12.119
This idea of, like, you want things to kind of speak to people, right?

00:04:12.119 --> 00:04:13.639
This emotional resonance.

00:04:13.639 --> 00:04:17.959
I want to feel a connection, I want to be connected to my passion, and I want to be

00:04:17.959 --> 00:04:18.959
engaged.

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:24.600
So with these three concepts in mind, there are a couple of different ways that you can

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:30.200
start to create community spaces using these concepts.

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:35.519
And there's sort of three event types to me that really lend themselves well to this idea

00:04:35.519 --> 00:04:39.679
of trust, accessibility, and emotional resonance.

00:04:39.679 --> 00:04:41.920
The first is think-pair-share.

00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:47.679
So the idea of think-pair-share is this cooperative learning strategy, and it starts with individual

00:04:47.679 --> 00:04:52.519
reflection first, and then you're paired together, and you kind of discuss the problem, and then

00:04:52.519 --> 00:04:55.799
you come out to a larger group, and then you're kind of discussing, like, the things that

00:04:55.799 --> 00:04:56.799
you've learned.

00:04:56.799 --> 00:05:03.399
Then you have data storytelling, and here we have, like, these very bite-sized projects,

00:05:03.399 --> 00:05:08.640
and they're really focused on the idea of, like, data to meaning, so they're really focused

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:13.000
on visualization, not necessarily so much on the coding themselves.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.359
And then finally, you have the sort of more traditional tried-and-true hackathons, right?

00:05:17.359 --> 00:05:20.200
Fast-paced team-building, problem-solving, and that sort of thing.

00:05:20.200 --> 00:05:25.000
And I'm going to break down each one of these, and I'm going to kind of have a flow throughout

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:30.279
of how you can interweave trust, accessibility, and emotional resonance for each one of these

00:05:30.279 --> 00:05:34.160
event types with a story, an example.

00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:39.880
So the first I'm going to talk about is think-pair-share, and this story is going to be about a group

00:05:39.880 --> 00:05:42.519
of high school students that I worked with.

00:05:42.519 --> 00:05:46.880
It was a completely virtual and mostly asynchronous for most of the summer, and then we kind of

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:51.440
got together at the end of the summer in person, and the first thing I noticed when we were

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:56.880
together in person was, while they really did understand, like, the functions and kind

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:02.200
of what they did, they got really stuck on, like, how do I actually apply this in the

00:06:02.200 --> 00:06:03.760
real world to, like, real things?

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:05.679
So that was the first thing.

00:06:05.679 --> 00:06:08.880
The other thing was they also really didn't want to ask questions, right?

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:14.320
They'd been asynchronous and online the entire time, so nobody wanted to say anything.

00:06:14.320 --> 00:06:15.760
Nobody wanted any questions.

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:17.540
They were very quiet.

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:21.119
And I thought, like, a think-pair-share might be a great way to sort of hit both of these

00:06:21.119 --> 00:06:29.839
issues, and so the first thing I did is before we even did the think-pair-share, I actually

00:06:29.839 --> 00:06:32.679
asked folks, like, hey, what are your goals?

00:06:32.679 --> 00:06:33.679
What are your interests?

00:06:33.679 --> 00:06:34.679
What are your hobbies?

00:06:34.679 --> 00:06:35.679
Like, what do you want to get out of this?

00:06:35.679 --> 00:06:40.600
I asked, like, a whole set of questions, and then I actually built coding challenges around

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:44.279
these problems of interest.

00:06:44.279 --> 00:06:50.880
Then I provided a bunch of different coding examples in a bunch of different formats,

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:57.640
and so that way each pair got to pick the challenge that really kind of fit them, and

00:06:57.640 --> 00:07:00.399
they got to roll with that.

00:07:00.399 --> 00:07:05.640
The other thing that was really important to me is to really hit home this idea of mistakes

00:07:05.640 --> 00:07:11.239
are learning opportunities, not failures, and I even demoed a bunch of my old code from

00:07:11.239 --> 00:07:16.279
grad school that is full of terrible, terrible mistakes, and kind of walked through, like,

00:07:16.279 --> 00:07:20.279
and here's what I've learned about that, and here's, you know, how I've built new things,

00:07:20.279 --> 00:07:24.959
and it was great that I did these mistakes, because now I get to do more cool things.

00:07:24.959 --> 00:07:26.839
But also all questions are valuable.

00:07:26.839 --> 00:07:31.519
Honestly, a lot of the times when people ask me questions, I'm like, oh, I never even thought

00:07:31.519 --> 00:07:32.519
about it.

00:07:32.519 --> 00:07:33.519
Let's try it together.

00:07:33.519 --> 00:07:36.760
Like, it's a great space to learn together, but also, like, more often than not, if you

00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:39.839
have a question, somebody else has pretty much the same question.

00:07:39.839 --> 00:07:43.239
So why not learn it together?

00:07:43.239 --> 00:07:49.440
The other thing that I really like personally about think-pair-share is the think part,

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:53.600
and you know, this is meant to be, like, the space where we really get to slow down and

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:59.640
process things internally, but I like it a lot, because I'm dyslexic, so I'm not a

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:04.160
fast reader, and often what would happen, like, when I was trying to learn things, like,

00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:06.799
you would get shown some code, and everyone would already have the solution, and I'm like,

00:08:06.799 --> 00:08:08.480
I'm still reading what's happening.

00:08:08.480 --> 00:08:10.399
I don't know where we are.

00:08:10.399 --> 00:08:13.359
So like the think part really does have it baked into there.

00:08:13.359 --> 00:08:15.839
You have this pause time, this down time.

00:08:15.839 --> 00:08:21.600
Let's sit with our thoughts, slow down for a second, see what this means.

00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:34.559
The other thing is that I built prompts for discussion, so not coding prompts, but actual

00:08:34.559 --> 00:08:40.359
discussion prompts, because I really wanted them to focus on this idea of, like, problem-solving

00:08:40.359 --> 00:08:47.000
and different ways to problem-solve and how to work through the challenge together, rather

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:51.080
than, like, oh, let's get really nitty-gritty on the code.

00:08:51.080 --> 00:08:56.039
And then I kind of further brought that home for the group discussion, so we celebrated

00:08:56.039 --> 00:08:59.640
process over product, so what I mean by that is, like, we really celebrated, like, that's

00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:03.320
a really cool way to think about that, or I didn't even think about, like, using it

00:09:03.320 --> 00:09:04.320
that way.

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:05.320
This is really great.

00:09:05.320 --> 00:09:07.239
And it was, again, less about, like, the code itself.

00:09:07.239 --> 00:09:12.359
I mean, but they were writing code, learning code, building code.

00:09:12.359 --> 00:09:18.520
One thing I really loved about this is, so after we did the think-pair-share, I had always

00:09:18.520 --> 00:09:20.919
had virtual office hours throughout the whole summer.

00:09:20.919 --> 00:09:25.440
Almost none of the students ever came and just sat there and did nothing for an hour.

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:30.239
But after this event, they were coming to virtual office hours, and I was like, this

00:09:30.239 --> 00:09:31.640
is great.

00:09:31.640 --> 00:09:35.000
And then when we would do live demos, they were asking questions.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:39.320
But the other cool thing is this was the third year I'd run this program, but the first year

00:09:39.320 --> 00:09:44.440
I'd done this, and they actually started their final projects early, like, before they needed

00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:45.440
to start them.

00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:50.679
So I have a hunch that maybe they felt a lot more confident in getting things done,

00:09:50.679 --> 00:09:54.280
even sort of, like, without guidance.

00:09:54.280 --> 00:09:58.880
The next example I'm going to talk about is using data storytelling.

00:09:58.880 --> 00:10:03.520
So I had a medical librarian program that I worked with for the past two years that

00:10:03.520 --> 00:10:08.119
was really focused on building more technical skills.

00:10:08.119 --> 00:10:14.679
And by this point, we'd actually had a couple of coding workshops already, but one thing

00:10:14.679 --> 00:10:18.320
that I really noticed with the medical librarians, so a lot of them, they'd been in their job

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:19.320
for a really long time.

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:21.280
They were super confident in what they did.

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:24.280
And then we were teaching them coding, and they would kind of freeze.

00:10:24.280 --> 00:10:27.400
They would be like, I don't even want to do this because I'm going to do it wrong.

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:29.000
What if I break something?

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:33.640
There was just this real, like, concern about doing it wrong.

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:36.440
And it kind of kept coming up over and over again.

00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:40.119
And the other thing that also I noticed is, like, for some of them, they were like, I

00:10:40.119 --> 00:10:42.119
don't know how this actually does apply to my job.

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:47.479
Like, I'm not really getting a connection of, like, this work to what I do.

00:10:47.479 --> 00:10:51.159
So I thought a data storytelling activity might be a great way to kind of bridge both

00:10:51.159 --> 00:10:53.200
of those gaps.

00:10:53.200 --> 00:10:57.940
So I started with a data set that was actually a health data set, some that they'd actually

00:10:57.940 --> 00:11:02.479
already come across a couple of times, and that's where we kind of built the heart of

00:11:02.479 --> 00:11:06.400
our data storytelling activity.

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:11.280
The other thing that I did was I actually put them on teams, and they did have differing

00:11:11.359 --> 00:11:15.320
levels of sort of skills and skill sets that they were bringing.

00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:18.039
And I really tried to iterate that this was a strength, right?

00:11:18.039 --> 00:11:21.880
Because in order to sort of analyze data to tell a story with data, you need lots of different

00:11:21.880 --> 00:11:22.880
skills, right?

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:26.239
You need to have the subject matter skills to understand the data, you need to be able

00:11:26.239 --> 00:11:30.159
to interpret patterns, you need to understand, like, the ethics of the data.

00:11:30.159 --> 00:11:35.520
There's so many components, and you need all of those things, and you can build them together.

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:39.640
But the thing that I love about data storytelling is it kind of gets at this idea of, like,

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:40.640
wrong.

00:11:41.440 --> 00:11:45.760
In data storytelling, there are so many ways that you can tell a story with data, right?

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:48.119
And this was, like, huge survey data.

00:11:48.119 --> 00:11:51.640
So there's tons of things that you can say about this data, there's tons of ways to explore,

00:11:51.640 --> 00:11:53.760
there's tons of plots to explore.

00:11:53.760 --> 00:11:56.320
So there is no wrong way, per se.

00:11:56.320 --> 00:11:59.559
There's many fun, right ways.

00:11:59.559 --> 00:12:06.280
The other thing was I built some notebooks with lots of prompts, so lots of bits of pre-made

00:12:06.280 --> 00:12:10.719
code, like, hey, you could try this, or you could do this, here's a plot or two.

00:12:10.719 --> 00:12:14.280
But also prompts about the data, like, what if, you know, we do this, have you thought

00:12:14.280 --> 00:12:15.719
about the data like that?

00:12:15.719 --> 00:12:17.679
Like data exploration prompts as well.

00:12:17.679 --> 00:12:22.039
So they weren't kind of starting completely from nowhere.

00:12:22.039 --> 00:12:25.679
The other thing was I really highlighted interactive tools.

00:12:25.679 --> 00:12:31.559
So one of my favorite packages is Esky, and it's really cool, because it actually takes

00:12:31.559 --> 00:12:37.359
ggplot and turns it into a point and click, drop and drag, and it spits out code for you,

00:12:37.359 --> 00:12:38.359
basically.

00:12:38.359 --> 00:12:43.599
So it is reproducible, but it makes it interactive, and you're now not so focused on code, you're

00:12:43.599 --> 00:12:47.119
focused on, like, how can I tell a story with this data?

00:12:47.119 --> 00:12:51.559
So I kind of, like, removed that part of the stickiness.

00:12:51.559 --> 00:12:56.840
The other thing is I really, really encouraged personal connection and creativity in this

00:12:56.840 --> 00:12:57.840
activity.

00:12:57.840 --> 00:13:01.140
And what I meant by that was, like, you know, is there a particular bit of data that speaks

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:02.859
to work you already do?

00:13:02.859 --> 00:13:07.219
Is there a particular bit that speaks to something personally for you?

00:13:07.219 --> 00:13:11.859
But even more so, like, for their final presentations, I basically let them present however they

00:13:11.859 --> 00:13:12.859
liked.

00:13:12.859 --> 00:13:15.900
Some of them made infographics, some of them just did the plots, some of them talked about

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:18.179
the ethics behind the data with the plots.

00:13:18.179 --> 00:13:22.020
They sort of got to come up with their creative strategies for this.

00:13:22.020 --> 00:13:25.340
The thing that's really fun about this is I just told you this entire program was virtual,

00:13:25.340 --> 00:13:28.340
and yet here's a picture of me with two of my librarians.

00:13:28.340 --> 00:13:33.299
And what happened was after this event, a couple of librarians got so excited and so

00:13:33.299 --> 00:13:37.820
engaged in this that they ended up actively seeking out other activities, and this happened

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:40.580
to be a data for good workshop.

00:13:40.580 --> 00:13:43.900
And they showed up, and they were, like, we're excited to be part of the data community,

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:48.460
and it was just really great to see how much more confidence they had after this.

00:13:48.460 --> 00:13:53.099
My final example is going to be hackathons, partially because this is my favorite thing.

00:13:53.099 --> 00:13:56.780
I ran probably over 70 of them by now.

00:13:56.780 --> 00:13:59.859
And this particular example is a bit of an oldie but a goodie.

00:13:59.859 --> 00:14:06.099
So when I was first participating in hackathons, I noticed that I was usually the only female

00:14:06.099 --> 00:14:07.099
team lead.

00:14:07.099 --> 00:14:09.539
There were other women participating, but not leading teams.

00:14:09.539 --> 00:14:12.219
So when I started running hackathons, I really wanted to change that.

00:14:12.219 --> 00:14:16.859
So I started talking to a bunch of different women's coding groups, women's science groups,

00:14:16.859 --> 00:14:20.799
and we came up with the idea with a women-led hackathon, and this was really sort of something

00:14:20.799 --> 00:14:22.719
we built together from day one.

00:14:22.719 --> 00:14:25.539
This is what we kind of came up with.

00:14:25.580 --> 00:14:31.979
And we were really excited to mentor and be mentored by other women.

00:14:31.979 --> 00:14:35.979
We also focused a lot more on collaboration versus competition, although, to be fair,

00:14:35.979 --> 00:14:39.820
all of my hackathons, for the most part, are pretty much collaborative, because I want

00:14:39.820 --> 00:14:40.820
to build community.

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:43.099
But that doesn't mean that we didn't celebrate success, right?

00:14:43.099 --> 00:14:46.739
We had lots of fun awards around all sorts of different things to sort of say, like,

00:14:46.739 --> 00:14:49.419
hey, you've done amazing stuff.

00:14:49.419 --> 00:14:53.700
But also I built the team specifically to make sure that there was, you know, coders

00:14:53.700 --> 00:14:57.099
as well as scientists and different levels of expertise, and they could really build

00:14:57.099 --> 00:14:58.859
community together that way.

00:14:58.859 --> 00:15:04.179
Finally, we made sure that the projects had varying level of difficulty, but also subject

00:15:04.179 --> 00:15:07.659
matter, so that way there really was hopefully a project for everyone.

00:15:07.659 --> 00:15:12.219
I also built multiple sort of, like, team roles.

00:15:12.219 --> 00:15:18.820
So we had everything from, like, data munger to, you know, analyst to subject matter expert.

00:15:18.820 --> 00:15:23.580
Like, people made logos for their teams so they could practice art, all sorts of things.

00:15:23.580 --> 00:15:27.020
And I also made sure that there was a bunch of different, like, shiny tools and cloud

00:15:27.020 --> 00:15:31.219
computing tools to help them collaborate together.

00:15:31.219 --> 00:15:35.179
And the final thing was, like, for our final presentations, I really wanted them to have,

00:15:35.179 --> 00:15:37.580
like, outside the box, like, crazy ideas.

00:15:37.580 --> 00:15:44.219
And they loved having this, you know, no-risk place to explore and take risks.

00:15:44.219 --> 00:15:48.299
But what I loved the most about this hackathon is most of the participants were men who'd

00:15:48.299 --> 00:15:53.099
never been in a hackathon before, and they explicitly said they were participating because

00:15:53.099 --> 00:15:54.979
this is a women-led hackathon.

00:15:54.979 --> 00:15:59.059
And most of us actually still continue to talk today, work together, collaborate together.

00:15:59.059 --> 00:16:04.539
But my favorite part is a couple of the women in this picture formed another team and participated

00:16:04.539 --> 00:16:07.299
in MIT Hacking Medicine, and they won.

00:16:07.299 --> 00:16:08.299
So I was like, yes!

00:16:08.299 --> 00:16:09.299
This is fantastic!

00:16:09.299 --> 00:16:12.900
So why does this work?

00:16:12.900 --> 00:16:18.780
So if you have trust, you build safe social learning spaces, right?

00:16:18.780 --> 00:16:19.900
And this builds persistence.

00:16:19.900 --> 00:16:23.979
So even if I get stuck, like, I know I have an Accountability buddy who's cheering me

00:16:23.979 --> 00:16:27.020
on, and when they get stuck, I'm cheering them on, right?

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:31.099
So when you get frustrated, like, somebody's like, yes, you got this, and when you're frustrated,

00:16:31.099 --> 00:16:32.099
you swap.

00:16:32.099 --> 00:16:33.739
But also, like, you now have a safe community.

00:16:33.739 --> 00:16:36.659
When you do get stuck, you're like, I know I can ask somebody, and they're not gonna

00:16:36.659 --> 00:16:37.659
be like...

00:16:37.659 --> 00:16:46.580
Also, right, so we want clear points of entry, supportive tools, lower barriers of entry,

00:16:46.580 --> 00:16:48.760
and that really helps more people feel welcome.

00:16:48.760 --> 00:16:51.520
And finally, emotions just make things stickier, right?

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:55.359
You're more likely to learn things when you feel connected to them.

00:16:55.359 --> 00:16:57.799
So three ways you can start today.

00:16:57.799 --> 00:17:00.679
Curiosity questions, instead of where are you from, what's your name, ask them what

00:17:00.679 --> 00:17:01.679
they're interested in.

00:17:01.679 --> 00:17:06.079
What-if questions, open-ended questions, to make it like you are interested, you want

00:17:06.079 --> 00:17:07.079
to explore.

00:17:07.079 --> 00:17:12.079
Also, multi-participation formats, right?

00:17:12.079 --> 00:17:17.000
You can share by a giant whiteboard with sticky notes instead, so you can be social without

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:18.239
talking to people.

00:17:18.239 --> 00:17:22.160
And finally, connect activities to real problems, even if it's something small, like a dataset,

00:17:22.160 --> 00:17:23.160
a question, something.

00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:26.719
And you don't need to do all three of these, even just one is great.

00:17:26.719 --> 00:17:32.079
So I hope today that I have really helped you come into my idea of, like, coding is

00:17:32.079 --> 00:17:33.680
about what you can imagine and create together.

00:17:33.680 --> 00:17:35.719
If you want to work with me, check it out there.

00:17:35.719 --> 00:17:37.319
I actually have an initiative right now.

00:17:37.319 --> 00:17:41.680
We'd love to have mentors, datasets, and student participants.

00:17:41.680 --> 00:17:42.680
Thank you so much.

00:17:42.920 --> 00:17:43.920
Thank you guys.

00:17:50.920 --> 00:17:53.239
I think we have time for one question.

00:17:53.239 --> 00:17:57.880
When building teams with different skills, how do you decide how to put people together?

00:17:57.880 --> 00:18:00.739
Or do you just let them get together by themselves?

00:18:00.739 --> 00:18:06.560
Yeah, so most of the events I run are where I specifically build the teams, because I

00:18:06.560 --> 00:18:11.959
really do want them to work outside of their, sort of, field, but also have interdisciplinary

00:18:11.959 --> 00:18:14.959
teams, but also have different skills that they're building together, so I really try

00:18:14.959 --> 00:18:18.719
to make sure they're people who have never been in a hackathon before, people who have,

00:18:18.719 --> 00:18:22.819
people who have, sort of, not as confident with coding, those who are, and I'm really

00:18:22.819 --> 00:18:27.239
trying to make sure that these teams that are going to work together and build together.

00:18:27.239 --> 00:18:28.239
Excellent.

00:18:28.239 --> 00:18:29.239
Thank you so much.

00:18:29.239 --> 00:18:30.520
Let's thank Alyssa again.

